message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The rubbery, large testicle in a male with a history of cryptorchidism suggests testicular cancer. Among the options, only increased glandular breast tissue is associated with testicular cancer, specifically with non-seminomatous germ cell tumors, which are more common in patients with a history of cryptorchidism. Increased radio-femoral delay is associated with coarctation of the aorta, increased placental alkaline phosphatase is associated with choriocarcinoma, and decreased smell perception is associated with Kallmann syndrome.
